Jeffery.<br>
First, it's most refreshing to read some a response that isn't personal attack, from someone who presents his point of view logicly and dispassionately .  <br><br>
&lt;&lt;The Vietnamese condemned French colonialism and drove them out. They considered the Americans to be motivated by colonialism also. In many ways this was an accurate perception. We wanted to dominate Vietnam.&gt;&gt;<br><br>
Agree with the first part---it's historical fact.  Disagree with the rest---your opinion, and welcome to it.  My experience was that they diffinetly did not view us as being motivated by colonialism.  Our treatment of them was totally different from the French and really there simply insnt any comparison. This confused and sometimes drove them to distraction trying to figure out why we were there.  Altruism is without historic precedent there and I've seem them trying desperately to find a hidden motive for what we said and did.  It was very amusing sometimes.<br><br>
 &lt;&lt;We didn't want to establish a democratic government. We wanted to establish a pro-American government. .........why have we supported dictatorships, brutal regimes, and monarchies all over the world?&gt;&gt;<br>
   Excellant point.  First I disagree on us not wanting to establish a democratic government.  As to the second part, it's just expediency.  The &quot;enemy of my enemy is my friend&quot; or &quot;the lessor of two evils&quot; approach.  We were allies with Stalin against Hitler for this reason.  But our &quot;intentions&quot; were/are good.   That's what gets us in trouble.  If we just played the standard power politics without the good intentions, we'd might do better and for certain, both our allies and our enemies  would understand us better.  The &quot;good intentions&quot; part is what makes us so unpredictable.  They both hate that.<br><br>
 &lt;&lt;When the United States got involved in Somalia,...&gt;&gt;<br>
      Somilia, Haiti, etc. are perfect examples of &quot;good intentions&quot; poorly executed.  Don't want to get into the never ending discussion of national interests.  Here you are using your military for &quot;humanitarian&quot; reasons.  OK, not what they are trained for, but if that's what the nation wants, they'll do it.  The problem arose from the fact that you couldn't do the one properly without military action and it went down hill from there.  Politicians confused the two, resticting the later in the name of the former.  Bad idea.<br><br>
.&lt;&lt; This was what happened in Vietnam.&gt;&gt;<br>
     In part correct, if you use my analysis of mixing the politics and tacics.<br><br>
 &lt;&lt;Actually Vietnam was worse in the premise, much less the result, since Somalia had a humanitarian dimension which was totally absent in Vietnam.&gt;&gt;<br>
Totally disagree.  If the humanitarian/political aspect had been missing--ie, a straight forward military action we would have won it within three years.<br><br>
 &lt;&lt;In Vietnam, we invaded another country, and took part in a civil war.&gt;&gt;<br>
You've read my posts on this and obviously I disagree on both aspects.<br><br>
&lt;&lt; I presume you had sympathy for the Bosnian Muslims. &gt;&gt;<br>
   Indeed I did.  I supported sending them arms to defend themselves.  <br><br>
&lt;&lt;At the peak of the Bosnian War,&gt;&gt;<br>
Don't think we've seen the peak yet.<br><br>
 &lt;&lt;did you advocate sending 500,000 American ground troops into the heart of the conflagration?&gt;&gt;<br>
No----send them the weapons to defend themselves.  That's what they wanted.<br><br>
&lt;&lt;The United States did not have altruistic motives in Vietnam. Even if you thought it did, you would still deeply regret our involovement since it was a dismal failure. 57,600 Americans were killed, and we achieved absolutely nothing. &gt;&gt;<br>
Disagree with altuistic motives---as I've stated.  I do deeply regret that do to the unnessassry involvement of our politicians combined with the supine position assumed by our military leaders, that indeed it was for naught.   <br>
Thanks for the discussion without the name calling.  Enjoyed it.
